{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01D9ia8vBVgvDFEzH31YNQVi","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tConfiguration Handling\n2\t======================\n3\t\n4\tApplications need some kind of configuration.  There are different settings\n5\tyou might want to change depending on the application environment like\n6\ttoggling the debug mode, setting the secret key, and other such\n7\tenvironment-specific things.\n8\t\n9\tThe way Flask is designed usually requires the configuration to be\n10\tavailable when the application starts up.  You can hard code the\n11\tconfiguration in the code, which for many small applications is not\n12\tactually that bad, but there are better ways.\n13\t\n14\tIndependent of how you load your config, there is a config object\n15\tavailable which holds the loaded configuration values:\n16\tThe :attr:`~flask.Flask.config` attribute of the :class:`~flask.Flask`\n17\tobject.  This is the place where Flask itself puts certain configuration\n18\tvalues and also where extensions can put their configuration values.  But\n19\tthis is also where you can have your own configuration.\n20\t\n21\t\n22\tConfiguration Basics\n23\t--------------------\n24\t\n25\tThe :attr:`~flask.Flask.config` is actually a subclass of a dictionary and\n26\tcan be modified just like any dictionary::\n27\t\n28\t    app = Flask(__name__)\n29\t    app.config['TESTING'] = True\n30\t\n31\tCertain configuration values are also forwarded to the\n32\t:attr:`~flask.Flask` object so you can read and write them from there::\n33\t\n34\t    app.testing = True\n35\t\n36\tTo update multiple keys at once you can use the :meth:`dict.update`\n37\tmethod::\n38\t\n39\t    app.config.update(\n40\t        TESTING=True,\n41\t        SECRET_KEY='192b9bdd22ab9ed4d12e236c78afcb9a393ec15f71bbf5dc987d54727823bcbf'\n42\t    )\n43\t\n44\t\n45\tDebug Mode\n46\t----------\n47\t\n48\tThe :data:`DEBUG` config value is special because it may behave inconsistently if\n49\tchanged after the app has begun setting up. In order to set debug mode reliably, use the\n50\t``--debug`` option on the ``flask`` or ``flask run`` command. ``flask run`` will use the\n51\tinteractive debugger and reloader by default in debug mode.\n52\t\n53\t.. code-block:: text\n54\t\n55\t    $ flask --app hello run --debug\n56\t\n57\tUsing the option is recommended. While it is possible to set :data:`DEBUG` in your\n58\tconfig or code, this is strongly discouraged. It can't be read early by the\n59\t``flask run`` command, and some systems or extensions may have already configured\n60\tthemselves based on a previous value.\n61\t\n62\t\n63\tBuiltin Configuration Values\n64\t----------------------------\n65\t\n66\tThe following configuration values are used internally by Flask:\n67\t\n68\t.. py:data:: DEBUG\n69\t\n70\t    Whether debug mode is enabled. When using ``flask run`` to start the development\n71\t    server, an interactive debugger will be shown for unhandled exceptions, and the\n72\t    server will be reloaded when code changes. The :attr:`~flask.Flask.debug` attribute\n73\t    maps to this config key. This is set with the ``FLASK_DEBUG`` environment variable.\n74\t    It may not behave as expected if set in code.\n75\t\n76\t    **Do not enable debug mode when deploying in production.**\n77\t\n78\t    Default: ``False``\n79\t\n80\t.. py:data:: TESTING\n81\t\n82\t    Enable testing mode. Exceptions are propagated rather than handled by the\n83\t    the app's error handlers. Extensions may also change their behavior to\n84\t    facilitate easier testing. You should enable this in your own tests.\n85\t\n86\t    Default: ``False``\n87\t\n88\t.. py:data:: PROPAGATE_EXCEPTIONS\n89\t\n90\t    Exceptions are re-raised rather than being handled by the app's error\n91\t    handlers. If not set, this is implicitly true if ``TESTING`` or ``DEBUG``\n92\t    is enabled.\n93\t\n94\t    Default: ``None``\n95\t\n96\t.. py:data:: TRAP_HTTP_EXCEPTIONS\n97\t\n98\t    If there is no handler for an ``HTTPException``-type exception, re-raise it\n99\t    to be handled by the interactive debugger instead of returning it as a\n100\t    simple error response.\n101\t\n102\t    Default: ``False``\n103\t\n104\t.. py:data:: TRAP_BAD_REQUEST_ERRORS\n105\t\n106\t    Trying to access a key that doesn't exist from request dicts like ``args``\n107\t    and ``form`` will return a 400 Bad Request error page. Enable this to treat\n108\t    the error as an unhandled exception instead so that you get the interactive\n109\t    debugger. This is a more specific version of ``TRAP_HTTP_EXCEPTIONS``. If\n110\t    unset, it is enabled in debug mode.\n111\t\n112\t    Default: ``None``\n113\t\n114\t.. py:data:: SECRET_KEY\n115\t\n116\t    A secret key that will be used for securely signing the session cookie\n117\t    and can be used for any other security related needs by extensions or your\n118\t    application. It should be a long random ``bytes`` or ``str``. For\n119\t    example, copy the output of this to your config::\n120\t\n121\t        $ python -c 'import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex())'\n122\t        '192b9bdd22ab9ed4d12e236c78afcb9a393ec15f71bbf5dc987d54727823bcbf'\n123\t\n124\t    **Do not reveal the secret key when posting questions or committing code.**\n125\t\n126\t    Default: ``None``\n127\t\n128\t.. py:data:: SECRET_KEY_FALLBACKS\n129\t\n130\t    A list of old secret keys that can still be used for unsigning, most recent\n131\t    first. This allows a project to implement key rotation without invalidating\n132\t    active sessions or other recently-signed secrets.\n133\t\n134\t    Keys should be removed after an appropriate period of time, as checking each\n135\t    additional key adds some overhead.\n136\t\n137\t    Flask's built-in secure cookie session supports this. Extensions that use\n138\t    :data:`SECRET_KEY` may not support this yet.\n139\t\n140\t    Default: ``None``\n141\t\n142\t    .. versionadded:: 3.1\n143\t\n144\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_NAME\n145\t\n146\t    The name of the session cookie. Can be changed in case you already have a\n147\t    cookie with the same name.\n148\t\n149\t    Default: ``'session'``\n150\t\n151\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN\n152\t\n153\t    The value of the ``Domain`` parameter on the session cookie. If not set, browsers\n154\t    will only send the cookie to the exact domain it was set from. Otherwise, they\n155\t    will send it to any subdomain of the given value as well.\n156\t\n157\t    Not setting this value is more restricted and secure than setting it.\n158\t\n159\t    Default: ``None``\n160\t\n161\t    .. warning::\n162\t        If this is changed after the browser created a cookie is created with\n163\t        one setting, it may result in another being created. Browsers may send\n164\t        send both in an undefined order. In that case, you may want to change\n165\t        :data:`SESSION_COOKIE_NAME` as well or otherwise invalidate old sessions.\n166\t\n167\t    .. versionchanged:: 2.3\n168\t        Not set by default, does not fall back to ``SERVER_NAME``.\n169\t\n170\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_PATH\n171\t\n172\t    The path that the session cookie will be valid for. If not set, the cookie\n173\t    will be valid underneath ``APPLICATION_ROOT`` or ``/`` if that is not set.\n174\t\n175\t    Default: ``None``\n176\t\n177\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY\n178\t\n179\t    Browsers will not allow JavaScript access to cookies marked as \"HTTP only\"\n180\t    for security.\n181\t\n182\t    Default: ``True``\n183\t\n184\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE\n185\t\n186\t    Browsers will only send cookies with requests over HTTPS if the cookie is\n187\t    marked \"secure\". The application must be served over HTTPS for this to make\n188\t    sense.\n189\t\n190\t    Default: ``False``\n191\t\n192\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_PARTITIONED\n193\t\n194\t    Browsers will send cookies based on the top-level document's domain, rather\n195\t    than only the domain of the document setting the cookie. This prevents third\n196\t    party cookies set in iframes from \"leaking\" between separate sites.\n197\t\n198\t    Browsers are beginning to disallow non-partitioned third party cookies, so\n199\t    you need to mark your cookies partitioned if you expect them to work in such\n200\t    embedded situations.\n201\t\n202\t    Enabling this implicitly enables :data:`SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE` as well, as\n203\t    it is only valid when served over HTTPS.\n204\t\n205\t    Default: ``False``\n206\t\n207\t    .. versionadded:: 3.1\n208\t\n209\t.. py:data:: SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE\n210\t\n211\t    Restrict how cookies are sent with requests from external sites. Can\n212\t    be set to ``'Lax'`` (recommended) or ``'Strict'``.\n213\t    See :ref:`security-cookie`.\n214\t\n215\t    Default: ``None``\n216\t\n217\t    .. versionadded:: 1.0\n218\t\n219\t.. py:data:: PERMANENT_SESSION_LIFETIME\n220\t\n221\t    If ``session.permanent`` is true, the cookie's expiration will be set this\n222\t    number of seconds in the future. Can either be a\n223\t    :class:`datetime.timedelta` or an ``int``.\n224\t\n225\t    Flask's default cookie implementation validates that the cryptographic\n226\t    signature is not older than this value.\n227\t\n228\t    Default: ``timedelta(days=31)`` (``2678400`` seconds)\n229\t\n230\t.. py:data:: SESSION_REFRESH_EACH_REQUEST\n231\t\n232\t    Control whether the cookie is sent with every response when\n233\t    ``session.permanent`` is true. Sending the cookie every time (the default)\n234\t    can more reliably keep the session from expiring, but uses more bandwidth.\n235\t    Non-permanent sessions are not affected.\n236\t\n237\t    Default: ``True``\n238\t\n239\t.. py:data:: USE_X_SENDFILE\n240\t\n241\t    When serving files, set the ``X-Sendfile`` header instead of serving the\n242\t    data with Flask. Some web servers, such as Apache, recognize this and serve\n243\t    the data more efficiently. This only makes sense when using such a server.\n244\t\n245\t    Default: ``False``\n246\t\n247\t.. py:data:: SEND_FILE_MAX_AGE_DEFAULT\n248\t\n249\t    When serving files, set the cache control max age to this number of\n250\t    seconds. Can be a :class:`datetime.timedelta` or an ``int``.\n251\t    Override this value on a per-file basis using\n252\t    :meth:`~flask.Flask.get_send_file_max_age` on the application or\n253\t    blueprint.\n254\t\n255\t    If ``None``, ``send_file`` tells the browser to use conditional\n256\t    requests will be used instead of a timed cache, which is usually\n257\t    preferable.\n258\t\n259\t    Default: ``None``\n260\t\n261\t.. py:data:: TRUSTED_HOSTS\n262\t\n263\t    Validate :attr:`.Request.host` and other attributes that use it against\n264\t    these trusted values. Raise a :exc:`~werkzeug.exceptions.SecurityError` if\n265\t    the host is invalid, which results in a 400 error. If it is ``None``, all\n266\t    hosts are valid. Each value is either an exact match, or can start with\n267\t    a dot ``.`` to match any subdomain.\n268\t\n269\t    Validation is done during routing against this value. ``before_request`` and\n270\t    ``after_request`` callbacks will still be called.\n271\t\n272\t    Default: ``None``\n273\t\n274\t    .. versionadded:: 3.1\n275\t\n276\t.. py:data:: SERVER_NAME\n277\t\n278\t    Inform the application what host and port it is bound to.\n279\t\n280\t    Must be set if ``subdomain_matching`` is enabled, to be able to extract the\n281\t    subdomain from the request.\n282\t\n283\t    Must be set for ``url_for`` to generate external URLs outside of a\n284\t    request context.\n285\t\n286\t    Default: ``None``\n287\t\n288\t    .. versionchanged:: 3.1\n289\t        Does not restrict requests to only this domain, for both\n290\t        ``subdomain_matching`` and ``host_matching``.\n291\t\n292\t    .. versionchanged:: 1.0\n293\t        Does not implicitly enable ``subdomain_matching``.\n294\t\n295\t    .. versionchanged:: 2.3\n296\t        Does not affect ``SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN``.\n297\t\n298\t.. py:data:: APPLICATION_ROOT\n299\t\n300\t    Inform the application what path it is mounted under by the application /\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014Vg4bcXYywh7sABGiAFdYD","session_id":"780e4baa-3aa8-4b0d-9a7b-e4e22ccb96cd","uuid":"a2aa42da-6a70-48c4-9dea-e67b83127551","timestamp":"2026-03-31T21:25:24.318Z"}
