{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PVVKVdVdoyHzxYpXnX9rC3","type":"tool_result","content":"400\t.. versionadded:: 0.6\n401\t   ``MAX_CONTENT_LENGTH``\n402\t\n403\t.. versionadded:: 0.7\n404\t   ``PROPAGATE_EXCEPTIONS``, ``PRESERVE_CONTEXT_ON_EXCEPTION``\n405\t\n406\t.. versionadded:: 0.8\n407\t   ``TRAP_BAD_REQUEST_ERRORS``, ``TRAP_HTTP_EXCEPTIONS``,\n408\t   ``APPLICATION_ROOT``, ``SESSION_COOKIE_DOMAIN``,\n409\t   ``SESSION_COOKIE_PATH``, ``SESSION_COOKIE_HTTPONLY``,\n410\t   ``SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE``\n411\t\n412\t.. versionadded:: 0.9\n413\t   ``PREFERRED_URL_SCHEME``\n414\t\n415\t.. versionadded:: 0.10\n416\t   ``JSON_AS_ASCII``, ``JSON_SORT_KEYS``, ``JSONIFY_PRETTYPRINT_REGULAR``\n417\t\n418\t.. versionadded:: 0.11\n419\t   ``SESSION_REFRESH_EACH_REQUEST``, ``TEMPLATES_AUTO_RELOAD``,\n420\t   ``LOGGER_HANDLER_POLICY``, ``EXPLAIN_TEMPLATE_LOADING``\n421\t\n422\t.. versionchanged:: 1.0\n423\t    ``LOGGER_NAME`` and ``LOGGER_HANDLER_POLICY`` were removed. See\n424\t    :doc:`/logging` for information about configuration.\n425\t\n426\t    Added :data:`ENV` to reflect the :envvar:`FLASK_ENV` environment\n427\t    variable.\n428\t\n429\t    Added :data:`SESSION_COOKIE_SAMESITE` to control the session\n430\t    cookie's ``SameSite`` option.\n431\t\n432\t    Added :data:`MAX_COOKIE_SIZE` to control a warning from Werkzeug.\n433\t\n434\t.. versionchanged:: 2.2\n435\t    Removed ``PRESERVE_CONTEXT_ON_EXCEPTION``.\n436\t\n437\t.. versionchanged:: 2.3\n438\t    ``JSON_AS_ASCII``, ``JSON_SORT_KEYS``, ``JSONIFY_MIMETYPE``, and\n439\t    ``JSONIFY_PRETTYPRINT_REGULAR`` were removed. The default ``app.json`` provider has\n440\t    equivalent attributes instead.\n441\t\n442\t.. versionchanged:: 2.3\n443\t    ``ENV`` was removed.\n444\t\n445\t.. versionadded:: 3.10\n446\t    Added :data:`PROVIDE_AUTOMATIC_OPTIONS` to control the default\n447\t    addition of autogenerated OPTIONS responses.\n448\t\n449\t\n450\tConfiguring from Python Files\n451\t-----------------------------\n452\t\n453\tConfiguration becomes more useful if you can store it in a separate file, ideally\n454\tlocated outside the actual application package. You can deploy your application, then\n455\tseparately configure it for the specific deployment.\n456\t\n457\tA common pattern is this::\n458\t\n459\t    app = Flask(__name__)\n460\t    app.config.from_object('yourapplication.default_settings')\n461\t    app.config.from_envvar('YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS')\n462\t\n463\tThis first loads the configuration from the\n464\t`yourapplication.default_settings` module and then overrides the values\n465\twith the contents of the file the :envvar:`YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS`\n466\tenvironment variable points to.  This environment variable can be set\n467\tin the shell before starting the server:\n468\t\n469\t.. tabs::\n470\t\n471\t   .. group-tab:: Bash\n472\t\n473\t      .. code-block:: text\n474\t\n475\t         $ export YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS=/path/to/settings.cfg\n476\t         $ flask run\n477\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n478\t\n479\t   .. group-tab:: Fish\n480\t\n481\t      .. code-block:: text\n482\t\n483\t         $ set -x YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS /path/to/settings.cfg\n484\t         $ flask run\n485\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n486\t\n487\t   .. group-tab:: CMD\n488\t\n489\t      .. code-block:: text\n490\t\n491\t         > set YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS=\\path\\to\\settings.cfg\n492\t         > flask run\n493\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n494\t\n495\t   .. group-tab:: Powershell\n496\t\n497\t      .. code-block:: text\n498\t\n499\t         > $env:YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS = \"\\path\\to\\settings.cfg\"\n500\t         > flask run\n501\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n502\t\n503\tThe configuration files themselves are actual Python files.  Only values\n504\tin uppercase are actually stored in the config object later on.  So make\n505\tsure to use uppercase letters for your config keys.\n506\t\n507\tHere is an example of a configuration file::\n508\t\n509\t    # Example configuration\n510\t    SECRET_KEY = '192b9bdd22ab9ed4d12e236c78afcb9a393ec15f71bbf5dc987d54727823bcbf'\n511\t\n512\tMake sure to load the configuration very early on, so that extensions have\n513\tthe ability to access the configuration when starting up.  There are other\n514\tmethods on the config object as well to load from individual files.  For a\n515\tcomplete reference, read the :class:`~flask.Config` object's\n516\tdocumentation.\n517\t\n518\t\n519\tConfiguring from Data Files\n520\t---------------------------\n521\t\n522\tIt is also possible to load configuration from a file in a format of\n523\tyour choice using :meth:`~flask.Config.from_file`. For example to load\n524\tfrom a TOML file:\n525\t\n526\t.. code-block:: python\n527\t\n528\t    import tomllib\n529\t    app.config.from_file(\"config.toml\", load=tomllib.load, text=False)\n530\t\n531\tOr from a JSON file:\n532\t\n533\t.. code-block:: python\n534\t\n535\t    import json\n536\t    app.config.from_file(\"config.json\", load=json.load)\n537\t\n538\t\n539\tConfiguring from Environment Variables\n540\t--------------------------------------\n541\t\n542\tIn addition to pointing to configuration files using environment\n543\tvariables, you may find it useful (or necessary) to control your\n544\tconfiguration values directly from the environment. Flask can be\n545\tinstructed to load all environment variables starting with a specific\n546\tprefix into the config using :meth:`~flask.Config.from_prefixed_env`.\n547\t\n548\tEnvironment variables can be set in the shell before starting the\n549\tserver:\n550\t\n551\t.. tabs::\n552\t\n553\t   .. group-tab:: Bash\n554\t\n555\t      .. code-block:: text\n556\t\n557\t         $ export FLASK_SECRET_KEY=\"5f352379324c22463451387a0aec5d2f\"\n558\t         $ export FLASK_MAIL_ENABLED=false\n559\t         $ flask run\n560\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n561\t\n562\t   .. group-tab:: Fish\n563\t\n564\t      .. code-block:: text\n565\t\n566\t         $ set -x FLASK_SECRET_KEY \"5f352379324c22463451387a0aec5d2f\"\n567\t         $ set -x FLASK_MAIL_ENABLED false\n568\t         $ flask run\n569\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n570\t\n571\t   .. group-tab:: CMD\n572\t\n573\t      .. code-block:: text\n574\t\n575\t         > set FLASK_SECRET_KEY=\"5f352379324c22463451387a0aec5d2f\"\n576\t         > set FLASK_MAIL_ENABLED=false\n577\t         > flask run\n578\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n579\t\n580\t   .. group-tab:: Powershell\n581\t\n582\t      .. code-block:: text\n583\t\n584\t         > $env:FLASK_SECRET_KEY = \"5f352379324c22463451387a0aec5d2f\"\n585\t         > $env:FLASK_MAIL_ENABLED = \"false\"\n586\t         > flask run\n587\t          * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000/\n588\t\n589\tThe variables can then be loaded and accessed via the config with a key\n590\tequal to the environment variable name without the prefix i.e.\n591\t\n592\t.. code-block:: python\n593\t\n594\t    app.config.from_prefixed_env()\n595\t    app.config[\"SECRET_KEY\"]  # Is \"5f352379324c22463451387a0aec5d2f\"\n596\t\n597\tThe prefix is ``FLASK_`` by default. This is configurable via the\n598\t``prefix`` argument of :meth:`~flask.Config.from_prefixed_env`.\n599\t\n600\tValues will be parsed to attempt to convert them to a more specific type\n601\tthan strings. By default :func:`json.loads` is used, so any valid JSON\n602\tvalue is possible, including lists and dicts. This is configurable via\n603\tthe ``loads`` argument of :meth:`~flask.Config.from_prefixed_env`.\n604\t\n605\tWhen adding a boolean value with the default JSON parsing, only \"true\"\n606\tand \"false\", lowercase, are valid values. Keep in mind that any\n607\tnon-empty string is considered ``True`` by Python.\n608\t\n609\tIt is possible to set keys in nested dictionaries by separating the\n610\tkeys with double underscore (``__``). Any intermediate keys that don't\n611\texist on the parent dict will be initialized to an empty dict.\n612\t\n613\t.. code-block:: text\n614\t\n615\t    $ export FLASK_MYAPI__credentials__username=user123\n616\t\n617\t.. code-block:: python\n618\t\n619\t    app.config[\"MYAPI\"][\"credentials\"][\"username\"]  # Is \"user123\"\n620\t\n621\tOn Windows, environment variable keys are always uppercase, therefore\n622\tthe above example would end up as ``MYAPI__CREDENTIALS__USERNAME``.\n623\t\n624\tFor even more config loading features, including merging and\n625\tcase-insensitive Windows support, try a dedicated library such as\n626\tDynaconf_, which includes integration with Flask.\n627\t\n628\t.. _Dynaconf: https://www.dynaconf.com/\n629\t\n630\t\n631\tConfiguration Best Practices\n632\t----------------------------\n633\t\n634\tThe downside with the approach mentioned earlier is that it makes testing\n635\ta little harder.  There is no single 100% solution for this problem in\n636\tgeneral, but there are a couple of things you can keep in mind to improve\n637\tthat experience:\n638\t\n639\t1.  Create your application in a function and register blueprints on it.\n640\t    That way you can create multiple instances of your application with\n641\t    different configurations attached which makes unit testing a lot\n642\t    easier.  You can use this to pass in configuration as needed.\n643\t\n644\t2.  Do not write code that needs the configuration at import time.  If you\n645\t    limit yourself to request-only accesses to the configuration you can\n646\t    reconfigure the object later on as needed.\n647\t\n648\t3.  Make sure to load the configuration very early on, so that\n649\t    extensions can access the configuration when calling ``init_app``.\n650\t\n651\t\n652\t.. _config-dev-prod:\n653\t\n654\tDevelopment / Production\n655\t------------------------\n656\t\n657\tMost applications need more than one configuration.  There should be at\n658\tleast separate configurations for the production server and the one used\n659\tduring development.  The easiest way to handle this is to use a default\n660\tconfiguration that is always loaded and part of the version control, and a\n661\tseparate configuration that overrides the values as necessary as mentioned\n662\tin the example above::\n663\t\n664\t    app = Flask(__name__)\n665\t    app.config.from_object('yourapplication.default_settings')\n666\t    app.config.from_envvar('YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS')\n667\t\n668\tThen you just have to add a separate :file:`config.py` file and export\n669\t``YOURAPPLICATION_SETTINGS=/path/to/config.py`` and you are done.  However\n670\tthere are alternative ways as well.  For example you could use imports or\n671\tsubclassing.\n672\t\n673\tWhat is very popular in the Django world is to make the import explicit in\n674\tthe config file by adding ``from yourapplication.default_settings\n675\timport *`` to the top of the file and then overriding the changes by hand.\n676\tYou could also inspect an environment variable like\n677\t``YOURAPPLICATION_MODE`` and set that to `production`, `development` etc\n678\tand import different hard-coded files based on that.\n679\t\n680\tAn interesting pattern is also to use classes and inheritance for\n681\tconfiguration::\n682\t\n683\t    class Config(object):\n684\t        TESTING = False\n685\t\n686\t    class ProductionConfig(Config):\n687\t        DATABASE_URI = 'mysql://user@localhost/foo'\n688\t\n689\t    class DevelopmentConfig(Config):\n690\t        DATABASE_URI = \"sqlite:////tmp/foo.db\"\n691\t\n692\t    class TestingConfig(Config):\n693\t        DATABASE_URI = 'sqlite:///:memory:'\n694\t        TESTING = True\n695\t\n696\tTo enable such a config you just have to call into\n697\t:meth:`~flask.Config.from_object`::\n698\t\n699\t    app.config.from_object('configmodule.ProductionConfig')\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_014Vg4bcXYywh7sABGiAFdYD","session_id":"780e4baa-3aa8-4b0d-9a7b-e4e22ccb96cd","uuid":"802234b5-a570-4f56-bb7c-9f48c96d84ed","timestamp":"2026-03-31T21:25:26.048Z"}
